\date{2025-12-11T21:04:30Z}

\author{sebastianttaylor}

\title{C418's \em{One} (2012): One of my Favourite Albums}

\p{There are select few albums which have inspired me or renewed a quiet sense of wonder at life; this is one such album. I discovered this record in early spring 2025 via the documentary (about the early days of Mojang) it was written for.}

\p{[C418](https://c418.org/) ([Daniel Rosenfeld](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C418)) published the album between Minecraft's volumes [Alpha](https://c418.org/albums/minecraft-volume-alpha/) (2011) and [Beta](https://c418.org/albums/minecraft-volume-beta/) (2013). The soundscape is a mixture of the two (brightness and whimsy from alpha, orchestral sound from beta). While my appreciation of the music certainly comes partly from the special feeling of Minecraft in its early days, I believe there is a strong case to be made for the music on technical grounds. This I will now attempt...}

\p{Firstly, this album is very long. There are 31 tracks, and 96 minutes of music. This requires Rosenfeld to present us with a great deal of variety, so that we don't become bored. There is the structure of a documentary to follow which does impose some structure on the music, many of the songs being quotes from the film "for the sake of making games", for example.}

\p{A crucial structural choice by Rosenfeld was to weave a few motifs throughout the album, reimagining them each time they come around. This makes the album feel like an experience. In classical music, this sort of structural integrity is required for most forms (sonata, theme + variations etc.), and is one of the reasons this genre has lasted so long. C418 calls this "Schönhören" in [his description](https://c418.org/albums/one/), which also details the specific tracks involved. They are: \em{Cliffside Hinson} -- \em{Danny Makes Chiptune} -- \em{Lawyer Cage Fight} -- \em{Social Lego} for the first theme, \em{Surface Pension} -- \em{Preliminary Art Form} -- \em{Post Success Depression} for the second and \em{Certitudes} -- \em{Lost Cousins} -- \em{One Last Game} -- \em{Wooden Love} for the third.}

\p{Making music by computer allows C418 to have absolute control over the music, and the listener's ear attunes to expect perfection in certain elements (rhythm, intonation, balance etc.). However, C418 presents a mastery and variety of texture which is not necessarily expected: I believe that the unique flavour in the music comes from C418's spontaneity with textural elements.}

\p{There are some straightforwardly stunning moments in the first few minutes: the deep bass note that introduces the first theme, and the solo piano chords that follow. In \em{Independent Accident} the music meditates for a while, before a sweeping string synth is added (c.f. \em{Subwoofer Lullaby}) in C418's inimitable way. Another similar thing occurs in \em{One Last Game}. Importantly, C418 takes great care with the individual voices in the sound, so that you can always follow just one and never get lost.}

\p{Whimsical/delightful textural choices are also present; the keypresses as percussion in \em{Surface Pension}, the percussion groove in \em{Certitudes}, and the empty ambience in \em{Diskdance}. A personal favourite is the mechanical clap track in \em{Danny Makes Chiptune} that creates some funky implied dissonances with the piano that enters shortly afterwards.}

\p{To say more would certainly spoil the album, and I hope I've convinced you that it's worth a listen. The original documentary is great for context also: [https://youtube.com/watch?v=ggCIGOQIoY4](https://youtube.com/watch?v=ggCIGOQIoY4).}
